<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Esther Smith, the girl who sings about ``The Boy
Next Door'' in ``Meet Me in St. Louis,'' was one of the most
sought-after roles of the new Broadway season. And one of the most
difficult to cast.
   ``Impossible to cast,'' insists Jay Binder, a top Broadway
casting agent and the man who helped put the performers on stage in
``Rumors'' and ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway,'' two of last season's
biggest hits.
   ``You have to find someone to play a role that was created
expressly for Judy Garland,'' says Binder, referring to the
legendary singer who was Esther in the memorable 1945 film version.
   ``What you have to do is not even try,'' he says. ``You have to
find someone who can play Esther and not Judy Garland.''
   Louis Burke, producer and director of the lavish musical, goes a
step further.
   ``I was looking for somebody who had her own personality that
would make us forget Garland,'' he says.
   During a 15-month, cross-country expedition, Burke and Binder
saw some 2,500 actresses. They had to listen to what seemed like
never-ending renditions of ``The Boy Next Door,'' ``Have Yourself a
Merry Little Christmas'' and ``The Trolley Song,'' the show's
best-known numbers.
   ``Today, if I hear `The Trolley Song,' I recoil in horror,''
Binder sighs.
   Among the first performers to audition back in June 1988 was a
former Junior Miss runner-up named Donna Kane, best known to New
York audiences as pert, tap-dancing little Ruby in the 1985 revival
of ``Dames at Sea.'' She didn't know it then, but she was Burke's
first choice for the role.
   ``The very first day I saw her, I knew there was a magic there
that was pretty extraordinary,'' Burke says now. ``That was my gut
reaction.
   ``And Donna actually was quite clever. She wore a very lovely
white lace dress with a blue sash around her waist that seemed to
fit the character. It impresses me when people prepare themselves
for auditions.''
   But Burke and Binder felt they had to continue the search,
looking at everyone who wanted to audition. So Kane didn't meet
again with Burke until February, when she auditioned twice more
with a series of different actors being considered for other roles
in the musical.
   ``You do everything over again,'' Kane says now. ``I sang the
same songs. I worked on a few more scenes. I was matched up with
different boys next door, sisters, mothers and fathers.''
   When it finally looked as if the show would arrive late last
season, financial problems forced its postponement until this fall.
   Kane went off to do ``Show Boat'' with the Minnesota Opera and a
successful concert of Rodgers and Hart's ``Babes in Arms'' at
Lincoln Center. When she returned to ``Meet Me in St. Louis,''
there was a fourth audition at the Neil Simon Theater and then a
final audition with Jason Workman, the actor chosen to play John
Truitt, the boy next door.
   ``Sometimes I thought it was really going to happen,'' she
recalls. ``And other times, I would say, `No, you can't count on
things until it is definite.'''
   It became definite only in late summer. Burke picked her to
appear in the musical with George Hearn and Charlotte Moore, who
play her parents, Milo O'Shea, who is her grandfather, and Betty
Garrett, who plays the Irish cook Katie.
   The stage version of ``Meet Me in St. Louis,'' on view at
Broadway's Gershwin Theater, has been trumpeted as a family show,
an old-fashioned American musical, something Broadway hasn't had
for a while. Its songwriters, Hugh Martin and Ralph Blane, have
expanded on their original movie score, adding 10 new songs.
   ``They definitely don't write music like this any more,'' Kane
says. ``The songs have melodies that are not only catchy and
memorable but emotional, too.
   ``There's a whole new bridge section to `The Boy Next Door'
which will be a surprise to people,'' she says. ``And there's a new
duet that Esther and the boy next door sing called `You Are for
Loving.' It's a beautiful melody, with a wonderful counterpoint.''
   ``Meet Me in St. Louis'' is Kane's first chance to originate a
role on Broadway. She had come to New York in 1984 after graduating
from Mount Holyoke as a political science major, but she had two
summers of stock in Vermont while in college.
   ``It's helped me in the theater to have a liberal arts
education,'' she says. ``As an actor, you have to analyze the text
critically. Besides, you can't just focus on the performing arts.''
   Her first job in New York was in a small musical called
``Madison Avenue,'' for which she answered an ad in the trade
papers. The job called for a Seven Sisters graduate and she fit the
bill.
   Next came ``Dames at Sea,'' which kept her occupied for nearly a
year. After that, there were productions of shows like ``My One and
Only'' in suburban New York and New Jersey.
   Kane wasn't idle while she waited for word from Burke and
Binder. She performed in a show in Boston, went on tour with
``Grease'' and moved to England for four months with her husband,
Mark Staples, an oil trader.
   Born in Beacon, N.Y., she was raised on Long Island and New
Jersey. Her parents were in education, not show business.
   ``My grandfather was a singer on the radio in the 1930s and
'40s,'' she says. ``I have his legacy, a piano, which is one of my
most cherished possessions.''
   The best advice Kane ever got from a voice teacher was when she
was 8 years old. The teacher told her mother, ``She's not doing
anything wrong. Leave her alone.''
   ``I was fortunate that I never had a style or technique imposed
on me,'' she says now.
   She doesn't worry about the comparisons to Judy Garland.
   ``I have not watched the movie on purpose during the rehearsal
process,'' she says. ``Growing up, I'd seen it many times, of
course. Some people in the cast have watched the film, others
haven't. But we're not trying to compare ourselves to it.
   ``I'm just trying to concentrate on the character of Esther, not
who played it. She's a very honest and very sincere person and to
be able to produce that vocally as well as act it out is just
great.''
</TEXT>
