<HEAD>Golden-Haired Women Awaken Nobel Laureates On Lucia Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNICA HAGLUND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Nobel Prize winners will wake up
Thursday in their hotel rooms surrounded by golden-haired young
women with candles on their heads, singing carols.
   It's Lucia Day, when Swedes brighten up the darkest period of
the year with celebrations embracing a Roman Catholic martyr and a
pre-Christian light festival.
   Before the Gregorian calendar was adopted, the feast of St.
Lucia was on the shortest day of the year. It commemorated a virgin
who was martyred in Syracuse, Sicily in 304 A.D.
   Pagan Swedes had their own mid-winter celebrations of light on
the year's shortest day. After Sweden was Christianized, the Roman
Catholic saint portrayed with lights in her golden hair became a
natural favorite.
   Nowadays Lucia processions occur throughout Sweden in offices,
on the streets and in schools. Singing young women with
electric-candle crowns lead the parade. People dressed as gnomes
hand out ginger snaps. Little ``star boys'' march along with
cone-shaped caps and star-topped wands.
   The festival falls three days after the Nobel Prize awards
ceremony. Many of the scientists, authors and statesmen are still
on hand, giving lectures and participate in seminars.
   Gun Lannergren, who has directed the processions at the Grand
Hotel for 15 years, said the laureates always are told in advance
about the 7 a.m. Lucia Day wakeup calls. With the laureates'
agreement, young music students are given keys to enter their rooms
and awaken them with song.
   ``The girls go from room to room and sometimes the laureates
join the procession in their pajamas to hear the girls sing once
again,'' said Lannergren.
   Traditionally, only Nobel Prize winners have enjoyed the private
spectacle. Other hotel clients can enjoy the singing later in the
morning when 20-25 young women perform a brief concert in a
separate room at the hotel.
   Swedish children sing for their parents on Lucia morning before
going to school to participate in choir performances. Young women
go about with strands of tinsel in their hair. Cookies, saffron
bread and mulled wine are consumed at impromptu parties.
   The popular Neapolitan song, ``Santa Lucia'' is always sung.
It's about the oldest part of Italy's Naples, the Santa Lucia
quarter which was named after the saint.
   Lucia is considered the patron saint of Syracuse and the
patroness of eyes. She is frequently shown with two eyes in a dish,
a possible reference to her martyrdom. The name Lucia comes from
the Latin word for light.
   The first accounts of Lucia celebrations in Sweden date to the
17th century.
   In the old medieval calendar the ``Lussi'' night between Dec.
12-13 was the longest night of the year and associated with
mysterious happenings. Country folk believed all children should be
christened before Lucia or the devil could take them from their
parents.
</TEXT>
