<HL> For Young Groupies,
The Who Is 'What?'
And Raffi Is the King
---
Pre-Schoolers Flock to Shows
Of Top Recording Artist
And Go Slightly Quackers
---
By Alan Freeman
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street  Journal</HL>
<DD> 06/29/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<DATELINE> PORTLAND, Ore.  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An hour before showtime at the Portland Civic Auditorium, Fred Trueax, assistant events director, is briefing his staff on crowd control.

   Try to keep excited fans from leaving their seats, Mr. Trueax instructs the 20 ushers gathered in the auditorium foyer.
"Believe it or not, these kids rush the stage," he warns.

   Soon, the fans stream into the 3,000-seat hall.
Some are clutching stuffed animals or sucking on pacifiers.
Others are crying.
All are very excited.

   These fans and their parents or teachers are here to see their idol, Raffi Cavoukian, known simply as Raffi.
Since he abandoned a struggling folk-singing career in Toronto a dozen years ago, Raffi has become North America's most popular children's entertainer.

   Long a superstar at Canadian day-care centers and nursery schools, Raffi is also attracting a big following in the U.S., where he has become the best-selling children's recording artist.

   "The kids' music industry in this country was almost dead, and he revived it," says Sherman Smith, the owner of the Ugly Duckling, a children's book and record store in Eugene, Ore.
"He's the foundation for the children's music industry in the U.S., and he's Canadian."

   Jimmy's mother found that out.
"I couldn't believe it when Jimmy wanted to come here" to the Portland concert, says Liz Russell.
"Here he is, a five-year-old groupie."
Jimmy wasn't alone.
"It was like trying to get tickets for The Who or the Rolling Stones," says Ms. Russell.

   "We had a three-hour lineup when the tickets went on sale the first day," says Carolyn Kelly, co-owner of a Portland children's bookstore that is promoting the concert here.
After selling out, the promoters added a second performance.
Jeffrey Creswell, a Portland teacher who plays Raffi tapes in his classroom, has come here with a group of 75, including almost all the pupils in his third-grade class and their families.
"He brings back to kids something we've robbed them of," says Mr. Creswell.
"In school, nobody sings to kids anymore."

   But this crowd certainly doesn't hesitate to sing.
From the time Raffi gets onto the stage with an enthusiastic "Hello, boys and girls" to the time he steps off a little over an hour later, the audience joins in with virtually every number.

   Dressed in a Hawaiian shirt and matching peaked cap, Raffi treats his fans to a mix of traditional children's songs, nonsense melodies and original ballads.

   "Are there any ducks in the crowd today?" he asks, and a chorus of quacks responds.
The audience enthusiastically provides lots more quacks to accompany Raffi as he sings "Five Little Ducks."
Ducks already figure in two other Raffi tunes.
Glenn Sernyk, Raffi's manager, says that Raffi's new album, due out this fall, will include yet another.
"We'll have a little more variety in the duck repertoire," he says.

   The nonsense songs are equally popular.
"I love to eat, eat, eat apples and bananas" turns into, "I love to eat, eat, eat, ee-pples and ba-nee-nees" and "I love to oot, oot, oot oo-pples and ba-noo-noos."

   Other songs require members of the audience to dance at their seats or "Shake My Sillies Out."
Raffi intertwines these fast-paced songs with slower ballads, including his best-known "Baby Beluga," a song about a whale.

   Gwynne Scholz, who runs Trespassers William, a children's bookstore in Albuquerque, N.M., says the mellow moments of Raffi's music make it superior to massmarketed "kiddies' music" that "winds up kids tighter than a drum."
That makes Raffi popular with parents, since the music is often played in the family car.
"Hell is being trapped for 600 miles with a {frenetic} licensed-character tape," Ms. Scholz says.

   Ms. Scholz and others link Raffi's success to a huge growth in the children's music industry.
"He definitely is the base line for kids' music," says Ms. Scholz.
"Nobody approaches him."

   "The stigma has been that if you can't perform for adults, you perform for kids, but this has changed in the past few years," says Gary Shontz of RosenShontz, a Vermont-based singing duo that caters to older children.
Mr. Shontz attributes most of the change to the success of Raffi and other Canadian children's performers.
"It all happened in Canada and has been spreading through the U.S.," he says.

   Born in Egypt 38 years ago to Armenian parents, Raffi emigrated with his family to Canada as a child.
In the late 1960s, he began performing as a singer-songwriter in Toronto coffeehouses.
"My folk-singing career was always a bit of a struggle," he says over a breakfast of chamomile tea prior to his two concerts here, part of a swing through the Pacific Northwest and western Canada.

   "Raffi was like John Denver part two," says Peter Goddard, the music critic for the Toronto Star.
"He came across as ultra-clean.
The times were wrong for him as an adult singer but right for him as a children's singer."

   In 1974, Raffi's mother-in-law suggested that he visit the nursery school where she taught.
He says, "My wife taught me three or four songs, including 'Baa Baa Black Sheep' and 'Eensy-Weensy Spider.'
I sat on a rug on the floor with a dozen kids and two or three teachers.
We had fun."

   Soon Raffi was performing in schools all over Toronto.
With $4,000, he recorded the album "Singable Songs for the Very Young."
"We thought it might do real well and sell 10,000 or 15,000 copies," says Ken Whiteley, who produced the album and plays with the Rise and Shine Band, which accompanies Raffi.

   So far, 320,000 copies have been sold in Canada, and although it is over 10 years old, it remains the top-selling of Raffi's seven albums in the U.S.
His eighth, "Everything Grows," is due out in August.

   Theoretically, there is a new audience every three years, says Raffi.
That hasn't been lost on A&amp;M Records, which distributes the records in the U.S. and Canada.
"It's turned out to be incredibly profitable for A&amp;M," says Mark Jaffe, the company's director of children's marketing.
He expects Raffi to sell over a million records and tapes in the U.S. this year.

   The appeal is definitely upscale.
In Canada, "It's just part of a yuppie's lifestyle to take the kids to a Raffi concert once a year," says Robert Bennett, a Toronto concert promoter who works closely with Raffi.

   The tradition is moving south.
The mother of a two-year-old who attended a recent concert in Santa Monica, Calif., says, "There were more Volvo station wagons in that parking lot than I ever saw before."

   All this is a bit of a surprise to the record industry, which figured that parents would never spend more than $5 on a children's record.
Raffi's records sell for up to $10 each, and one album recently came out on a compact disk.
"Within four days, we completely exhausted our supply," says A&amp;M's Mr. Jaffe.

   Although Raffi appeals primarily to pre-schoolers, children as old as 12 or 13 are at the concert here.
The older fans tend to be concentrated in smaller cities, says Mr. Sernyk, Raffi's manager.
"In the large metropolitan areas in the U.S., the cutoff age is six years old.
At seven, they're into Madonna."

   Despite his success, Raffi still refuses to become overly commercial.
Although he has produced one concert video, he has rejected offers to have his own TV show.

   "It doesn't please me to hear that kids watch my video endlessly," he says.
"Television isn't a friend of children.
Children need to play.
They need to interact with other people.
That's how they best find out about the world around them."

   Because of these beliefs, Raffi meets his fans after every performance, and this afternoon several hundred line up in the foyer, like children in a shopping mall waiting for Santa Claus.

   Seated with his legs crossed on a padded bench, Raffi signs autographs with a small heart beside his name and answers questions from the less bashful.
Some hug and kiss him or stroke his black beard.
"I have all your records and tapes," says five-year-old Curtis Wackerle.
"Well, really, I only have two.
I don't think anybody has all of them."

   The pace is exhausting, particularly when Raffi has two concerts in a day.
He usually is accompanied by his wife, Debi, who has given up schoolteaching to act as a "full-time consultant."

   Despite plans to perform in up to 80 U.S. cities starting this fall, Raffi expects to continue meeting his fans after every show.
"It's a wonderful opportunity for my audience to find out I'm a real person."

   Some aren't so sure.
Inevitably, one child asks, "How did you get off the tape?"
Another is more spiritual.
"Were you there when I was born?"

   Still others haven't quite mastered the etiquette of being a fan.
At a concert in Eugene, one little girl gets scolded by her mother soon after Raffi autographs her ticket stub.
"After you get an autograph," she says, "don't suck on it."

</TEXT>
