<HL>
   Rock of Ages:
   The Music Industry
   Is Getting Religion
   As Gospel Stars Shine
   ---
   Between Sacred and Profane,
   Singer Michael W. Smith
   Finds a Lucrative Niche
   ---
   An Act Even Parents Can Like
   ----
   By Monica Langley
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/11/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<MS>
CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)
</MS>
<IN>
BIOGRAPHY (BIO)
ENTERTAINMENT AND LEISURE (ENT)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<NS>
BIOGRAPHY (BIO)
</NS>
<RE>
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- With an hour to go before a scheduled
promotional bash at a big Manhattan record store, Michael W.
Smith, Geffen Records' newest hot property, is doing just
what you'd expect of a pop star: drinking, swallowing pills
and gossiping about the personal lives of rivals.
   But his drink is Diet Coke, his pills are Vitamin C and
odorless garlic, and the gossip is unusual:
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "I hear U-2 is Christian," a Geffen publicist says.
   "Three of them are," Mr. Smith replies. "I hear the bass
player isn't."
   Mr. Smith isn't the first clean-living Christian rock star
to come along, but he is the first to be signed by Geffen
Records -- the same power-house that handles Guns N' Roses
and Cher, among other secular acts. He is, in fact, at the
vanguard of a trend: Gospel singers, suddenly popular, are
making videos, appearing on late-night television and being
signed and promoted by the same big record companies that
saturate the airwaves with satanic speed metal and mysogynist
rap.
   It is a crossover movement as tricky as it is potentially
lucrative. It gives Mr. Smith and a handful of other
Christian stars, who heretofore sold their records from the
backs of vans at prayer meetings, a shot at money and
celebrity that earlier gospel performers never could have
dreamed of. But it gives them the awkward job of staking out
a middle ground between sacred and profane.
   So, when he is asked on "Live with Regis and Kathie Lee"
whether he is a pop or gospel performer, the blue-eyed,
33-year-old Mr. Smith squirms a little. "My faith is the most
important thing in my life. I just want to be a positive role
model," he says.
   Growth in the gospel-music business has been nothing short
of spectacular for the past decade. While the overall music
industry's revenue doubled between 1980 and 1990, the gospel
sector's nearly tripled, to around $500 million from $180
million.
   The rising popularity of gospel music was confirmed
recently when Billboard magazine, the all-important arbiter
of the music industry, revamped its chart monitoring system.
Billboard used to rely on record outlets to report sales
figures, which turned out to be skewed toward rock and pop
genres. In May Billboard switched to a technology that scans
bar codes on records at retail checkout counters and
electronically tallies actual numbers sold. One result was
that Billboard's chart suddenly included Mr. Smith's hit song
"Place in This World," which rose to fifth place.
   In fact, gospel musicians have been tilting toward secular
idioms to get more air play for at least a decade. "The
gospel music industry began copying secular acts in an
attempt to get others to see the light," says John Styll,
president of the Gospel Music Association. "The music was the
bait in fishing for souls."
   This has stretched the definition of gospel. The Gospel
Music Association's annual Dove awards now are given in 33
categories, from Praise and Worship to Heavy Metal to
Traditional Southern to Contemporary Christian -- the latter
category including Mr. Smith.
   Even so, until very recently gospel has been confined to a
world of its own. Even during the "Jesus movement" of the
1970s, when Christian rock bands appeared, inspirational
music was generally performed for gatherings of believers and
marketed on the spot or through Christian book stores.
   Which is one reason many of Mr. Smith's new fans don't
know he's a gospel singer at all. At a Manhattan record-store
promotion, 20-year-old fan Robert Kaiser, a college student
wearing an earring and a tie-dyed shirt, waits in line for
Mr. Smith's autograph. When the star reveals that this is his
seventh album, Mr. Kaiser blurts, "Wow, really?" On learning
the others were contemporary Christian records, Mr. Kaiser
says, "I don't believe in religion. I'm into an
anthropological view, but hey, that's cool. I still like your
song."
   Another reason for that kind of confusion -- and a key
component in the presentation of Michael W. Smith to the pop
world -- is the chastely steamy video he made to promote
"Place in This World." The video, produced by the same
company that does sizzling videos for Prince, shows a dreamy
Mr. Smith singing and playing the piano in the middle of the
desert while a young, pouting, gorgeous woman wanders around
in the sand. Eventually the two find each other, hold hands,
hug, and sort of nuzzle. The video reached the top five on
cable television's VH-1.
   "Making the video was hard at first," concedes Mr. Smith,
who is married and the father of four young children. "My
wife didn't like me hugging another woman, and my kids said
their mother should have done the video."
   Other fans have objections of their own. "I'm totally
against Michael going secular," says Angela Hoth, an
18-year-old fan from Joplin, Mo., who has written to him
about her concern. She listened to Mr. Smith's songs for
"encouragement" in the last year, especially after a friend
was killed in a car accident. "I worry that he will throw
away his message and lose his ministry to make it in the
secular market," she says.
   The West Side Christian Book Store in Knoxville, Tenn.,
won't play his album over its sound system for fear of
offending older and more fundamentalist customers. "Mr. Smith
may lose some Christian fans by going this route," says store
manager Edward Osborn. "He must be willing to pay that
price."
   Radio station WNDA in Huntsville, Ala., has pulled Mr.
Smith's records from its library and has sent a letter to
other stations and Christian bookstores urging them to follow
suit. In the letter, WNDA said it was particularly offended
that Mr. Smith and another hot gospel performer, Amy Grant,
acted as hosts of VH-1's Top 20 Countdown show. "Not only are
they pushing secular rock stars, but the show is sponsored by
. . . Budweiser," the letter said. It concluded: "The artists
will not return to our playlist until we are satisfied that a
change of heart has taken place and their testimony is
uncompromised by associations with secular rock, alcoholic
beverages and other destructive products."
   Mr. Smith's personal assistant keeps up a lively
correspondence with fans who accuse the singer of selling
out. In one letter to a disappointed fan, the assistant cited
the Bible's admonition to "let your light shine before men,
that they may see your good deeds and praise your Father in
heaven." Mr. Smith is following this scripture, the letter
suggested, adding, "Tons of prayer and accountability have
gone into this."
   Mr. Smith's music ranges from soothing ballads to
danceable pop tunes. His songs are sometimes sappy and always
positive in their outlook. He plays the piano and writes his
own songs, and while his voice has been criticized as "thin"
and "ragged," he is taking voice lessons.
   In his current album "Go West Young Man," Mr. Smith urges
listeners to run from the dangers of temptation ("When the
Evil goes East, Go West"). In his song "Old Enough to Know,"
he counsels against premarital sex. His new single, "For
You," is a chirpy confection about friendship ("When you're
up against the wall, you know I'll be here for you, for
you"). It is now moving up the charts.
   When Mr. Smith's label, Reunion Records, pitched him to
Geffen executives, they weren't immediately convinced. They
liked his catchy tunes, his moussed hair, his tight pants and
his Don Johnson stubble, but they made sure to send field
staff to check out his concerts last spring. "They wanted to
be sure he wasn't handing out Bibles," says Dan Harrell, one
of Mr. Smith's managers.
   They were convinced, and Reunion and Geffen signed a
"cross-marketing" agreement under which Reunion markets him
to Christian outlets and Geffen promotes him and distributes
his music to mainstream radio stations and retail stores.
Geffen suggested that he let his hair grow and call himself
"Michael W." rather than "Smitty," as he was known in gospel
circles.
   "Michael W. Smith is in the right place at the right
time," explains his manager, Michael Blanton. "Listeners are
tired of being hit over the head with dance and rap in recent
years, and now they're looking for melodies that they can
sing to and have meaning."
   "The recession has a lot to do with Michael's success,"
adds Terry Hemmings, president of Reunion Records. "When
times are tough, people are looking for a new angle and for
encouragement."
   The internal contradictions of his new stardom don't
appear to bother Mr. Smith. "I've been praying for mainstream
success for years," he says. "Now it's finally happening."
   Mr. Smith, a West Virginia native, moved to Nashville
after high school and broke into the music business as a
songwriter. At the same time he was penning gospel songs, he
was also using marijuana, LSD and cocaine. "I went off the
deep end and got into drugs, which messed me up for a while,"
he confides. His career went nowhere.
   Then in 1979, on the verge of a nervous breakdown, "I hit
the floor in my apartment face down and cried like a baby for
two hours," Mr. Smith recalls. "I got up, said a prayer to
God to turn me around and it's been different ever since."
   Soon, he had signed on as the keyboard player and
songwriter for Amy Grant. "I regret that I did drugs," Mr.
Smith now says, "but it has helped me relate to others with
similar problems due to drugs and low self-esteem."
   Now he is a role model of sorts. "There are almost no
pop-rock acts left that a parent can feel really good about
letting his children see," wrote a reviewer for the
Courier-Journal in Louisville, Ky., after attending Mr.
Smith's concert in May. "Smith offers an alternative."
   "Michael W. Smith is what top-40 radio desperately needs
right now," says Gary Bryan, a disk jockey for radio station
Z-100 in New York. "White, pop, middle-of-the-road hits
provide relief from rap and heavy metal, which are polarizing
our audience."
   This is not, however, just another case of a white
musician being promoted to skim the money off a black musical
idiom. American gospel music began when European settlers
brought over their psalms and folk melodies. "Later, when
plantation cultures tried to Christianize their slaves,
slaves added rhythm and soul to these songs," says Don Cusic,
author of "The Sound of Light: A History of Gospel Music."
   During Reconstruction and the 1890s, gospel music
continued to develop along racial lines, with white gospel
sticking close to hymns and black gospel evolving into
spirituals. The first recording labels devoted to gospel were
founded in 1916, and for decades the industry grew up outside
the mainstream music industry. Now, for the first time, the
gospel sector and major record labels are forming not-so-holy
alliances to exploit the changing marketplace.
   Besides the Reunion-Geffen agreement, Word Inc., the
biggest distributor of Christian music, has signed a
long-term distribution and marketing agreement with Epic
Records. Benson Music Group, an 89-year-old company that
started out selling religious pamphlets and sheet music, is
entering into a licensing agreement with A&amp;M Records. A&amp;M
made a similar pact with Perspective Records for the release
of "The Evolution of Gospel" by the Sounds of Blackness
(which produced a No. 1 hit on the rhythm-and-blues charts).
Amy Grant's "Baby Baby" hit No. 1 on the pop charts this
summer, and the gospel brother-and-sister duo BeBe and CeCe
Winans has become one of Capitol Records' hottest mainstream
acts, hitting No. 1 on Billboard's R&amp;B chart last week.
   Mr. Smith, for his part, is earning about $1 million a
year. He counts President Bush among his fans, and has
performed at the White House. He is reveling in his new
success, and he is comfortable in the curious musical
territory he inhabits. "I know if I'm too blatant about my
Christianity and talk about Jesus I won't succeed in the
mainstream," Mr. Smith says. "But hey, I'm not an evangelist,
I'm a singer."
</TEXT>
