<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: A collection of Mahalia Jackson's music is the centerpiece of
Columbia's 'Gospel Spirit' series  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  PAST; MUSIC; CELEBRITY; RECORD; RELIGION  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  ALMOST 20 years after her death, Mahalia Jackson remains the most famous name
in gospel music. Although she was only one of a number of great female
soloists, she was the one that crossed over to a white and mainstream
audience, which in turn meant major-label recordings, huge concerts in this
country and Europe and frequent television appearances. Given her wide and
enduring popularity, it is natural that Columbia records should make a Jackson
box set the flagship of their new "Gospel Spirit" series.;   Most people
remember Jackson as she was in her later years, and as she was on television.
A large woman, she would stand still on stage in a long dress. Her eyes would
be fixed on some point above and beyond the camera, and her voice and manner
proclaimed her majesty. Her solidity and respectability were those of a
classical singer, and she stood firmly for tradition and the old spirituals.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  PRAISE THE LORD AND PASS THE CDS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Recordings  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     In fact, though, Jackson was far from a traditionalist. Traditional black
church singing (like European-based church singing) was a group activity:
There were song leaders, but no real soloists. It was the rise of the
fundamentalist churches, with their more fervently emotional forms of worship,
that led to the gospel revolution.;   Newer than jazz, blues; While gospel is
spoken of today as a roots music, it is hardly 60 years old. Often described
as the basis of jazz and blues, it is newer than either and influenced by
both. Through the years, it has freely borrowed what it wanted from the
secular music of its day, adding and changing instrumentation and style while
always keeping an eye on its traditional roots.;   Jackson was part of the
first generation of innovators. She often sang traditional hymns, but she also
acknowledged her love for popular blues singers. She cited Bessie Smith as an
influence, and her singing was marked by blues phrasing, sliding between notes
and playing with the beat. In the '30s, many church people still regarded this
style of music as practically blasphemous, a "jazzing up" of church singing.;
 "Gospels, Spirituals and Hymns" is a two-CD box of Jackson's work for
Columbia in the '50s and '60s. Unlike the Robert Johnson and Bessie Smith
boxes that led Legacy's blues series, it is a selection rather than a
comprehensive collection, but it gives a decent overview of her work for the
label.;   Along with the Jackson box, "The Gospel Spirit" includes five discs
by less familiar artists. The Golden Gate Quartet and the Staple Singers show
early and late versions of the gospel quartet style, the main force in gospel
in the '40s and '50s. A live recording of the Abyssinian Baptist Gospel Choir
gives a good picture of gospel church singing.;   As with their blues series,
Columbia has made some odd choices. The reissues include an album by Paul
Robeson, who was many things but in no way a gospel singer, and four of the
six albums include secular material. Even the Jackson box includes a couple of
markedly inferior country-western songs while missing some of her strongest
work. Still, the gems far outweigh the clinkers.;   Jackson made her first
recordings in the '30s, then in the '40s had a string of hits on the Apollo
label. By the time she moved to Columbia, her style was firmly fixed and
accepted by the church, and her new audience took her for a "pure"
traditionalist. And yet innovation is audible in every note, and you're
continually struck by her inventiveness. On standard hymns and spirituals that
we all have heard countless times, it is impossible to guess from moment to
moment which note she will hit or when she will hit it.;   The Columbia box is
weighted toward traditional spirituals, to which Jackson increasingly turned
as she performed more for white audiences, but it also has a fine sampling of
original gospel songs, including four by Thomas A. Dorsey, "The Father of
Gospel Music.";   Gospel at its purest; As a pianist and singer, Dorsey was a
blues star before becoming one of the foremost gospel composers. Jackson
toured with him in the '40s, and his blues-influenced compositions were
perfectly suited to her style. Her version of his masterpiece, "Take My Hand,
Precious Lord," is gospel at its purest. Jackson sings at a very slow pace,
the slowness creating astonishing tension, teasing the words and making us
wait. Her voice promises immense power as it begins a phrase, then
surprisingly trails off into a wisp of melismatic falsetto.;   Between lines,
when Jackson pauses to breathe, the breaths are clearly audible -- not
theatrically overstated, just there, emphasizing her reality. It is the
difference between virtuosity and slickness. Nothing seems forced, and all of
it is used to drive home the message of the lyric. Familiar as the song is,
Jackson makes it sound new.;   Dorsey favored female soloists, but they were
far from the only stars in gospel. They were more familiar to non-gospel
audiences, but within the church their popularity was equaled by male
quartets, female and family groups and church choirs.;   "Swing Low Sweet
Chariot," an album of classic 1940s recordings of the Golden Gate Quartet,
definitely has that swing. The Gates were the top "jubilee" quartet, with
intricately jazzy vocal arrangements and unmatched rhythmic precision. Today,
the Gates sound somewhat dated, lacking the emotional force of the "hard"
gospel singers, but they show a side of gospel that is often overlooked -- its
consummate technical expertise and professionalism. Interestingly, the Gates'
rhythmic recountings of Bible stories bear an uncanny resemblance to modern
rap.  </TEXT>
