<TEXT>

   Ave Verum Corpus: Motets and Anthems by William Byrd (Collegium)
_ The Cambridge Singers, directed by John Rutter.
   Peter Philips: Paradisus Sacris Cantionibus (Accent) _ Currende,
directed by Erik Van Nevel.

   It is a comfort to have a recording at last of William Byrd's
``Non vos relinquam orphanos'' (``I will not leave you
comfortless'').
   Not even two minutes long, the motet is a little masterpiece of
Elizabethan music. Byrd combines a powerful feeling of sadness at
parting with a quietly affirmative ``alleluia.''
   Though he enjoyed the patronage of the Protestant Queen
Elizabeth I, Byrd clung to his Roman Catholic faith _ a devotion
that cost others their lives. ``Non vos relinquam,'' like most of
his later work, was written for Catholic services held in homes and
probably sung by musical amateurs.
   The Cambridge Singers, all adults, never approach the grandeur
of a cathedral choir of men and boys. However, with 71 minutes of
music and excellent notes, it's an exemplary addition to the small
but growing number of Byrd recordings.
   Peter Philips was also an English Catholic and may have been
Byrd's pupil before fleeing to the Low Countries, but he belonged
to another world.
   ``Ecce vicit leo'' (``Behold the lion''), the first of the 22
motets presented by the Belgian choir Currende, sounds very like
Giovanni Gabrieli's double-choir compositions for St. Mark's
Cathedral in Venice.
   The feeling is confident, extravagant, in contrast to Byrd's
restraint.
   Philips has been sorely neglected in recordings, and this
generous, polished recording is a solid beginning.
   _ By Robert Barr, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>

   ``Evidence'' (Chrysalis) _ Boo Hewerdine and Darden Smith

   This is a serendipitous musical meeting that almost makes the
Traveling Wilburys seem calculated by comparison.
   Boo Hewerdine fronts an obscure British band called the Bible.
Darden Smith is a struggling Texas singer-songwriter. In New York
City for the 1988 New Music Seminar, they were introduced by a
mutual friend, hit it off and began writing songs together. It took
just eight days to write a terrific album's worth of songs.
   ``Evidence'' exudes good feeling. This is folk-rock with a
smile, music with the spark of inspiration close to the surface.
``Out of This World'' vividly evokes the walking-on-air feeling of
new love, and does it with such simplicity that nursery rhymes are
quoted for lyrics. On ``Reminds Me a Little of You,'' a listener
can practically feel the presence of the woman for whom the
narrator is pining.
   Like so many albums today, the acoustic guitar is the musical
centerpiece, with other instruments added for dashes of colors.
Call it the Tracy Chapman Effect. It allows the artists to sink or
swim solely on the strength of their songs. Of the 12 songs on this
record (a lucky 13 on CD), there's not a weak cut.
   ``I want my cake mixed in with my pie,'' Hewerdine and Smith
sing on the slightly absurd ``All I Want (Is Everything).'' Here's
hoping they get their wish.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>

   ``Human Soul'' (RCA) _ Graham Parker

   Graham Parker is one of those artists the critics love but most
of the public has never heard. He's too intelligent and quirky for
Top 40 and AOR stations, and not quite radical enough for many
college stations.
   That's where home stereos come in.
   ``Human Soul,'' Parker's 12th LP, will tickle your tape deck,
rev up your record player.
   He continues in the bright pop rock groove of his last album,
``The Mona Lisa's Sister,'' but here he quickens the pace on many
tracks and cranks up his colorful imagination.
   ``Little Miss Understanding'' kicks it off with danceable,
ska-inflected sounds and typical wordplay: ``You're a woman with a
crazy man, Like a wasp that's stuck in jam, But I won't sting you
if you don't sting me.''
   After a few ballads and pop songs, Parker closes out the ``Real
Side'' _ or Side 1 _ with ``Soultime.'' The ska sound comes back
bigger _ with horns reminiscent of The Specials _ and blends with a
reggae-ified beat (something he's dabbled in on other albums).
   But the real action is on the ``Surreal Side'' _ or Side 2.
   ``Everything Goes'' starts off a suite of five continuous songs
that are faster and darker than those on the flip side.
``Everything'' showcases Parker's unusual talent for combining
heavy lyrics with lighthearted, punchy melodies. To a sweet tune,
he sings about a serial killer and more mundane horrors.
   He jumps right into the hyped-up ``Sugar Gives You Energy,''
then a sardonic tale of suburbia, ``Daddy's a Postman'' and ``Green
Monkeys,'' a cryptic doodling about AIDS.
   The suite closes out with ``I Was Wrong,'' where the music stops
cold, sucked right out of existence.
   On the last cut, ``Slash and Burn,'' he bites hard, but he still
offers a head-bobbing beat.
   Parker gets more urgent with this LP than he did on his last
record or in his mellower ``Another Grey Area'' period around 1982.
The world could end dead in its tracks, just as this record does,
he suggests.
   But not if Parker can help it.
   _ By Giselle Price, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
