<LEADPARA>  IMAGINE living in a monastery and training for the Olympics at the same time,
and you get some idea of the young opera singer's life.;    Only one out of
10,000 aspiring singers makes it, according to estimates. Their dreams of
success demand that they work like crazy.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE ODDS OF OPERA STARDOM? 10,000 TO 1, APPROXIMATELY
WITH A SONG IN THEIR HEART  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Classical Music  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "Some companies will listen to 70 to 80 singers in a day," says upwardly
mobile baritone Eli Villanueva, 30, whose younger brother LeRoy has already
sung numerous San Francisco Opera roles. "The Central City Opera recently had
1,200 applicants. They listened to 400 of them to cast exactly 31 roles for
the summer season in Colorado.";    Villanueva was part of a baker's dozen of
such California aspirants -- a highly impressive group of pros in the 22-32
age range -- who were invited here this past weekend as Opera San Jose held
tryouts for next season.;    By operatic standards, they were still young. At
an age when pro football players hang up their helmets for good, opera singers
are just getting to maturity.;    A 'crazy idea' bears fruit;  The unique OSJ
concept tied in auditions with an intensive three-day training session that
scarcely left time for the exhilarated singers to breathe.;    What OSJ's
Irene Dalis called "this crazy idea of mine I've been trying to bring off for
years" is sure to be repeated if the weekend's success is any indication.
Finding the new contract singers-in-residence for all next season, she
reasoned, can't be based on the usual audition tape and live two-minute aria
rendition.;    To be picked takes training, practice, and more training.;
"What outside life?" That was the question posed by soprano Julie Kierstine,
30, about a singer's leisure time. "It's no different from the marathon
training. You can't get sick; you have to stay in shape all the time.";    You
need funding as well. Coaching sessions indispensable for learning roles cost
$30-$50 per hour, and in New York City the tab is around $100 per hour.;
You also have to study roles, be ready for any audition anywhere. The
Villanuevas of today have to stand and deliver in five languages, including
Russian. Kierstine herself spent a year-and-a-half polishing and honing an
aria from Stravinsky's "The Rake's Progress" for the OSJ's private "Showcase
'91," closing out the proceedings at the Rehearsal Hall Sunday night.;    The
backgrounds of the showcased singers vary. Lyric baritone Earl Patriarco is of
Philippine descent. Tenor Jose Medina, 27, from Tijuana, Mexico, and more
recently San Diego, has performed in zarzuelas, or Spanish musicals. San
Francisco soprano Marlynn Smith, 30, has sung spirituals. And baritone Darin
Adams, 22, of Menlo Park has logged a lot of church-choir work.;    "Four of
the 12 here auditioning were people of color," remarked OSJ Development
Director Elliot Klein to a comment that OSJ had hired very, very few non-white
singers over the years.;    The weekend offered master classes, coaching
sessions, language study, recitatives -- just about everything short of
death-scene lessons.;    The reaction to the training? "Fabulous," says
soprano Smith.;    But why sing an ancient foreign-focused art like opera at
all, especially since it's much easier for vocalists to find other less taxing
jobs?;    "Mental illness helps," is the tongue-in-cheek response from tenor
Ravil Atlas of San Jose, who recently sang the lead in the San Francisco "Les
Miserables.";    "Opera is theater," says Patriarco. "But it's also the
highest form of vocal music that there is.";    A life in the opera;  "Opera
is in a class by itself," says mezzo Sarah Blaze. It has the highest
requirements of all, she adds. "Much more so than musicals. And the music --
it doesn't compare!";    Opera also takes panache, like that of soprano
Patricia McAfee. When it came time for her grand finale, she deliberately
selected the aria "O don fatale," the same work that OSJ Director Irene Dalis
had sung in her operatic debut abroad more than three decades ago. Much to her
relief, Dalis lighted up with enthusiasm after McAfee's rendition.;    The
operatic life is full of misconceptions. Some singers were asked about their
pet fallacies about their art. Some favorites:;    (box) "You've gotta be fat
if you're an opera singer." (Baritone Matthew Carey).;    (box) "You must be
earning a lot of money." (McAfee);    (box) "A kid came up to me after I sang
an opera and asked, 'Where are your horns?' (Villanueva, about a fan expecting
Brunnhildes everywhere.)  </TEXT>
