<HEAD>Duo Says Fraud Was `Pact With Devil,' Claim They Were Seduced,
Victimized</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, `The German-born ...' to CORRECT that Pilatus
was raised in Germany; picks up 13th graf, `There was ...' SUBS
16th graf, `The pair ...' to CORRECT year to 1989, sted 1988. Pick
up 17th graf, `Singing coach ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The disgraced pop music duo Milli Vanilli
surrendered their best new artist Grammy Award on Tuesday and
claimed their phony act as lipsyncing front men was a ``pact with
the devil'' that victimized them.
   Rob Pilatus and Fabrice Morvan, whose stardom was shattered last
week with the revelation that they never sang on the debut Milli
Vanilli album, said they were seduced into the deceit because they
were poor, young and naive.
   ``You get something, but for that you make a pact with the
devil,'' Pilatus said at a news conference.
   ``We feel really, really sorry about our fans,'' he said. ``We
really love our fans ... We just hope that they understand that we
were young, that we just wanted to live the life the American
way.''
   The pair and manager Carsten Heyn charged that Arista Records
President Clive Davis knew they were faking. Arista has repeatedly
denied the claim. Heyn also said recording industry officials
worldwide knew of the deception.
   The pair presented a videotape of themselves recording the hit
song ``Girl You Know It's True'' in a studio last weekend, but that
was greeted with skepticism and yells from reporters to prove they
really could sing.
   Pilatus belted out a few lines from the song and Morvan joined
in with the rap portion of the tune.
   Trustees of the National Academy of Recording Arts &amp; Sciences
voted Monday to rescind Milli Vanilli's Grammy. The pair held up
their trophies Tuesday and declared they were returning them with
recommendation they go to the real singers.
   Academy president Michael Greene said giving the trophies to the
singers who actually sang was ``not a possibility.''
   Voice coach Seth Riggs, who said his clients include Michael
Jackson, Madonna and Stevie Wonder, gave a testimonial to the duo's
singing abilities, saying they were better than the men who
actually were recorded.
   Pilatus claimed he and Morvan were victimized because they were
living in poverty in a Munich housing project when German producer
Frank Farian offered them the deal. He said that at the time they
even had to steal food.
   Pilatus, who was born in New York and raised in Germany,
described in broken English a growing sense of guilt that came
along with stardom and money.
   ``There was everytime something that we had to lie,'' he said.
``We had very guilty complexes.''
   The album ``Girl You Know It's True'' sold 7 million copies
worldwide and made the two unknowns international stars. Pilatus
and Morvan, a native of the Caribbean island of Guadaloupe, are
both 25.
   Farian last week confirmed growing rumors that the duo did not
sing on the album. It actually featured the voices of vocalists
Johnny Davis, Brad Howell and Charles Shaw. Pilatus said Shaw's
role was minimal and the Grammy really belongs to Davis and Howell.
   The pair also lipsynced through an appearance on February's
Grammy show in Los Angeles when Milli Vanilli was honored as best
new artist of 1989.
   Singing coach Riggs said he was there and that Pilatus and
Morvan were ready to sing but were told to fake it. He did not know
who gave the order. The duo also did not say who it was.
   The duo's attorney, Alan Mintz, supported their claim that they
had pressed the producer to be allowed to actually sing and that
the producer only came forward with the truth because Pilatus and
Morvan were about to.
   Meanwhile, an Oakland woman who bought her son a Milli Vanilli
tape filed a class action lawsuit in state court Monday seeking a
refund for anyone in California who bought the group's recordings
or attended one of their concerts.
   In Illinois, Chicago college student Karen L. Smith on Tuesday
also sued in Cook County Circuit Court, claiming fraud because the
CDs she bought named Pilatus and Morvan as performers.
</TEXT>
