<LEADPARA>  IN A RECENT column on the East Bay hills, I mentioned a poignant phrase I'd
sung years ago, "From the hills I gather courage." I thought it was from a
hymn whose title eluded me. Turned out to be a Girl Scout song instead, a
vestige of my youth or my brief career as a Brownie summer camp counselor.;
As several veteran Girl Scouts told me, the song starts with the title line,
"Peace I Ask of Thee, O River." And the river in question -- surprisingly --
is the Kentucky River, not the biblical River Jordan.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SCOUTING FOR ROOT OF RECALLED SONG  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "Peace" is frequently requested when former Girl Scouts turn nostalgic,
says Marian Gade of Kensington, vice president of the San Francisco Bay Girl
Scout Council and a folk song enthusiast. First published in 1941, it appeared
in such venerable scout songbooks as "The Ditty Bag," as well as in a
California grade school text, "Music for Living Around the World" in 1958.;
The words were written by a woman with the marvelous name of Glendora Gosling.
She and composer Viola Wood were taking a training cruise for Girl Scout
leaders on a river boat on the Kentucky River, explains Barbara Smith at scout
headquarters in New York. When the boat pulled over for a stop, Glendora and
Viola climbed to the top of a hill and -- inspired -- came back with a new
song. And it's made old Girl Scouts misty-eyed ever since -- even when they've
forgotten half the words or what a ditty bag ever was. (Oh, you knew  a ditty
bag was a small cloth bag used by sailors -- or old Girl Scouts -- to carry
personal items of gear.); (hbox);    CAMP FIRE, meanwhile, reminds us that
they are a separate and worthy organization. During February, 200 Camp Fire
youth in the Tri-Cities are selling mints, Almond Roca and almond caramel
clusters outside banks and supermarkets.;    Boys have been in Camp Fire since
the 1970s, leader Susan Blincoe says, "and it's especially frustrating for the
boys to be confused with Girl Scouts when people say, 'I've already bought
cookies.' ";    Another fact of Camp Fire evolution you might not know: Blue
Birds have been phased out in the last couple of years and replaced with the
Starflight program.; (hbox);    NEW-FOUND FUND FOLKS on the block: Shelter
Against Violent Environments' development director, John Ryder, came aboard
last month from the San Francisco Boys and Girls Club. He's already promoting
SAVE's fund-raiser at Francesco's in Oakland on May 15. That would be "Hunks
With a Heart" -- lunch with former Oakland Raiders John Vella, Tom Keating,
Carleton Oates, Dan Medlin, Marv Hubbard, Gary Weaver and George Buehler. For
information, call SAVE at (415) 794-6056. . . . At Serra Center, the
development director is Mim Carlson, formerly with the San Francisco Society
for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals. Serra's recent first art show by
developmentally disabled adults was so successful that 20 works by Serra
clients are now in a lively exhibit on the third floor of Fremont City Hall
through March 15. Colors and brushwork by artists like Pat McGuire and
Margaret Van Ark show a sure sense of design. Prices are modest and the
framing is better than many gallery shows I've covered.; (hbox);    MOREAU
HIGH SCHOOL in Hayward draws some 400 of its students -- about a third of the
student body -- from the Tri-City area. Janet Avila, a 12-year Moreau parent,
alerts us that the annual President's Ball moves off campus for the first time
March 2. The elegant event will be at the Sequoyah Country Club in Oakland, as
befits the school's 25th anniversary. The John A. Raimondi Volunteer of the
Year award goes to Kip Wixson of Castro Valley. The new Alumni Recognition
Award honors Doug Uchikura of Alamo and Frank Montenegro. The latter is a
27-year-old Fremont teacher who has cared for his five youngest siblings since
his parents died in 1988. For ball tickets at $150 a person, call (415)
582-5831.; (hbox);    GRADUATION is nearly four months away, but four Fremont
high schools already are planning sober all-night grad parties on campus.
Parents and teachers are seeking money, prize donations and volunteer time at
Irvington, Mission San Jose, Kennedy and American high schools. You know the
June graduation accident headlines related to drugs and alcohol. You know the
interviews with grieving classmates. Check with your parent group.  </TEXT>
